    English Russian Phrases
    English
  русский
    pronunciation guide
        Always pronounce...
       a as in "start",
  NOTE:
       g as in "big",
 The normal form of the pronoun "you" when speaking to a child is "ty".
   kh as in "loch",
   The normal form of the pronoun when speaking to more than one person is "vy".
   i as in "elite",
  This form is also used as a polite form of address for people you don't know very well.
  o as in "not",
 For anyone familiar with French, it's like "tu" and "vous".
      u as in "flute",
  You will find instances of both forms in the list below.
       zh as in the s in "pleasure";
 If you happen to use "vy" when just speaking to one of your Children,
   roll the r;
  they may look a bit surprised; that's all.
       wherever you see y not immediately followed by a vowel, pretend you're on Merseyside and say "eh", it's about the nearest we've got to the Russian vowel ы;
   note that all Russian words are heavily stressed on one syllable, which is shown by the underlinings in the pronunciation guide,
  and that unstressed o is pronounced more like the u in "up";
         ...and you won’t go too far wrong.
  It's not an exact science. They will giggle!
